  <Scenario>
    <message Tick="1"   Text="Lesson one, By this point you should have already ran the tutorial"/>
    <message Tick="20"  Text="First we will discuss what a packet is"/>
    <message Tick="40"  Text="A packet has a few main component; a Header and a Datagram"/>
    <message Tick="60"  Text="Your first two flags are these two main components"/>

    <message Tick="99" Text=""/>
    <message Tick="100" Text="Now where abouts does a packet reside? The TCP/IP Stack"/>
    <message Tick="120" Text="This stack has 4 layers. application, transport, network and link"/>
    <message Tick="150" Text="Application Layer"/>
    <message Tick="160" Text="The Application layer is the highest layer and is where high level protocols such as SSH and FTP reside"/>
    <message Tick="200" Text="Transport Layer"/>
    <message Tick="210" Text="The Transport layer is responcible for communication between systems, this is where TCP and UDP reside"/>
    <message Tick="260" Text="Network layer"/>
    <message Tick="270" Text="The Network layer is hop to hop, this is where IP is located"/>
    <message Tick="320" Text="Link Layer"/>
    <message Tick="330" Text="The Link layer is responcible for the transfer of data from one system to another and the integrity of that data, this is where the Ethernet protocols reside"/>
    <message Tick="400" Text="Your next flag is the layer that ip resides in fill in the underscores _____ Layer"/>
    
    <message Tick="449" Text=""/>
    <message Tick="450" Text="On the Link layer a MAC address is used as a unique identifier for each network interface"/>
    <message Tick="480" Text="A mac address is formatted as 6 bytes written in hexadecimal seperated by -'s or :'s"/>
    <message Tick="490" Text="For example: 4A:F8:99:23:E4:0A"/>
    <message Tick="500" Text="The next flag is the MAC Address of All 1's as formatted above"/>
    
    <message Tick="549" Text=""/>
    <message Tick="550" Text="When a packet is sent across a network using UDP or TCP they use Ports to communicate"/>
    <message Tick="600" Text="A port is much like a port in real life, data is directed there so it is forwarded to the correct destination"/>
    <message Tick="650" Text="The port 80 is a commonly used port for HTTP and 8080 for HTTPS"/>
    <message Tick="700" Text="Use the Packet sniffer to find out what two ports DHCP uses, submit them as two differen flags"/>

    <message Tick="750" Text="For this lesson the last thing you need to know is How an IPAddress is partitioned"/>
    <message Tick="790" Text="An IP is made up of a host address and a network address these can be found using the subnet mask"/>
    <message Tick="830" Text="for example with an ipaddress of 2.2.1.1 and a subnet mask of 2.2.0.0 the network address would be 192.168.0.0 and the host address would be 0.0.1.1"/>#
    <message Tick="880" Text="you may notice that this is done using a bitwise and between the IPaddress and the subnet mask"/>
    <message Tick="930" Text="the last flag is the network address of your current system"/>
    
    <message Tick="1000" Text="fin"/>
